    <section class="di-hero">
        <div class="di-breadcrumb"><a href="/landing">Rhythm Library System</a> › Drum Independence Exercises</div>
        <h1>Drum Independence Exercises</h1>
        <p class="di-hero-sub">Build Real Kit Coordination</p>
        <p class="di-hero-desc">Drum independence is the ability to move each limb independently while keeping a steady pulse. The Rhythm Library System builds this coordination progressively — starting with hand patterns and expanding to full kit application.</p>
        <button class="di-btn-primary" @onclick='() => Nav.NavigateTo("/")'>Practice Independence in the Free App →</button>
    </section>

    <div class="di-white">
        <div class="di-section">
            <div class="di-label">What Drum Independence Really Means</div>
            <h2>It is not about doing four things at once</h2>
            <p>Many drummers think of independence as the ability to do four completely different things simultaneously. In practice, <strong>independence is about keeping one part steady while another changes</strong>. That is a skill that can be built systematically.</p>
            <p>The Rhythm Library System develops independence by giving you a rhythmic framework — a sequence of note values — and asking you to apply different sticking patterns to it. Each pattern creates a different relationship between the hands and builds the neurological pathways that make coordination feel natural.</p>
            <p>Over time, these patterns transfer to the full drumset: right hand on the ride, left hand on the snare, feet on kick and hi-hat — all working together.</p>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class="di-gray">
        <div class="di-section">
            <div class="di-label">Coordination Stages</div>
            <h2>How independence develops</h2>
            <div class="di-stages">
                <div class="di-stage">
                    <div class="di-stage-num">1</div>
                    <div>
                        <h3>Foundation — hands only</h3>
                        <p>Start with both hands on the snare or practice pad. Focus entirely on the sticking pattern and the rhythm. Keep one hand steady while the other adapts to the phrase.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="di-stage">
                    <div class="di-stage-num">2</div>
                    <div>
                        <h3>Coordination — add the hi-hat foot</h3>
                        <p>Once the hands are comfortable, add a steady quarter note or eighth note on the hi-hat pedal with the left foot. Do not change the hand pattern — just add the foot underneath.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="di-stage">
                    <div class="di-stage-num">3</div>
                    <div>
                        <h3>Application — move around the kit</h3>
                        <p>Apply the hand pattern across the toms, cymbals, and snare while the feet hold a steady pulse. This is where sticking patterns become fills, solos, and groove variations.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class="di-white">
        <div class="di-section">
            <div class="di-label">Why Slow Practice Works</div>
            <h2>The science behind slow tempo training</h2>
            <p>When you practice at a slow tempo, your brain has time to consciously direct each movement. Repeated slow practice <strong>builds the neural pathways</strong> that eventually allow fast, automatic execution.</p>
            <p>Practicing too fast before the pattern is established teaches the brain to rush and approximate — which locks in sloppy technique that is hard to undo later.</p>
            <div class="di-tip-box">
                <strong>The rule:</strong> If you cannot play it slowly and evenly, you cannot play it fast and evenly. Slow is not a step backward — it is the fastest path to speed.
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class="di-gray">
        <div class="di-section">
            <div class="di-label">Daily Practice Routine</div>
            <h2>A 20-minute independence practice session</h2>
            <div class="di-routine">
                <div class="di-routine-row"><span class="di-routine-badge">5 min</span><div><strong>Slow coordination</strong><p>Both hands on snare at 60 BPM. Focus on even tone and steady tempo. No rushing.</p></div></div>
                <div class="di-routine-row"><span class="di-routine-badge">5 min</span><div><strong>Right-hand lead</strong><p>Play the current pattern right-hand lead through the full rhythm sequence.</p></div></div>
                <div class="di-routine-row"><span class="di-routine-badge">5 min</span><div><strong>Left-hand lead</strong><p>Same sequence, left-hand lead. This is often harder — that is exactly why it matters.</p></div></div>
                <div class="di-routine-row"><span class="di-routine-badge">5 min</span><div><strong>Kit application</strong><p>Move the pattern around the toms and cymbals. Right hand leads on ride or hi-tom, left on snare or floor tom.</p></div></div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class="di-dark">
        <div class="di-section" style="text-align:center;">
            <div class="di-label-light">Try It Now — Free</div>
            <h2 style="color:#fff;">Practice Independence in the Interactive App</h2>
            <p style="color:#b0c4de; max-width:620px; margin:0 auto 32px;">The free Rhythm Library System app lets you select any sticking pattern, set your tempo, and hear the pattern played back with real drum audio and live notation. Loop any measure to isolate difficult coordination spots.</p>
            <button class="di-btn-primary" style="font-size:1.05rem; padding:16px 40px;" @onclick='() => Nav.NavigateTo("/")'>Practice Independence in the Free App →</button>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class="di-white">
        <div class="di-section">
            <div class="di-label">Common Mistakes</div>
            <h2>What gets in the way of independence development</h2>
            <div class="di-mistakes">
                <div class="di-mistake"><div class="di-mistake-icon">⚠️</div><div><h3>Practicing too fast</h3><p>Speed before coordination locks in bad habits. Stay slow until the pattern is automatic.</p></div></div>
                <div class="di-mistake"><div class="di-mistake-icon">⚠️</div><div><h3>Skipping left-hand lead</h3><p>Most drummers favor right-hand lead. Left-hand lead practice is uncomfortable at first — that discomfort is the point.</p></div></div>
                <div class="di-mistake"><div class="di-mistake-icon">⚠️</div><div><h3>Not using a click track</h3><p>Independence without time is just randomness. The click track is part of the exercise, not optional.</p></div></div>
                <div class="di-mistake"><div class="di-mistake-icon">⚠️</div><div><h3>Moving to the kit too soon</h3><p>Build the hand pattern solidly before adding feet or moving to the kit. Layers added too early create confusion, not coordination.</p></div></div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class="di-white">
        <div class="di-section">
